## Description {#details}

Base class for instruction visitors.

<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/instruction">Instruction</a> visitors are used when you want to perform different actions for different kinds of instructions without having to use lots of casts and a big switch statement (in your code, that is).

To define your own visitor, inherit from this class, specifying your new type for the &#39;SubClass&#39; template parameter, and &quot;override&quot; visitXXX functions in your class. I say &quot;override&quot; because this class is defined in terms of statically resolved overloading, not virtual functions.

For example, here is a visitor that counts the number of malloc instructions processed:

/// Declare the class. Note that we derive from <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/instvisitor">InstVisitor</a> instantiated /// with <em>our new subclasses</em> type. /// struct CountAllocaVisitor : public <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/instvisitor">InstVisitor&lt;CountAllocaVisitor&gt;</a> &#123; unsigned Count; CountAllocaVisitor() : <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#a845e08be4b0320d66901a66b0c0e9509">Count(0)</a> &#123;&#125;

void <a href="#ab89f81b6570d21fd7eefa7b09439c149">visitAllocaInst(AllocaInst &amp;AI)</a> &#123; ++Count; &#125; &#125;;

And this class would be used like this: CountAllocaVisitor CAV; CAV.visit(function); NumAllocas = CAV.Count;

The defined has &#39;visit&#39; methods for <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/instruction">Instruction</a>, and also for <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/basicblock">BasicBlock</a>, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/function">Function</a>, and <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/module">Module</a>, which recursively process all contained instructions.

Note that if you don&#39;t implement visitXXX for some instruction type, the visitXXX method for instruction superclass will be invoked. So if instructions are added in the future, they will be automatically supported, if you handle one of their superclasses.

The optional second template argument specifies the type that instruction visitation functions should return. If you specify this, you <em>MUST</em> provide an implementation of visitInstruction though!.

Note that this class is specifically designed as a template to avoid virtual function call overhead. Defining and using an <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/instvisitor">InstVisitor</a> is just as efficient as having your own switch statement over the instruction opcode.

Definition at line 78 of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/ir/instvisitor-h">InstVisitor.h</a>.
